abstract: A look at news of interest in the San Francisco Bay Area.
snippet: A look at news of interest in the San Francisco Bay Area.
lead_paragraph: State Begins Releasing Inmates | In recent weeks, California has started an effort to reduce its inmate population of 167,000 by 6,500 this year. Some prisoners may be released early for completing drug or education programs. Part of the plan includes changing how the state handles parolees, many of whom, at the moment, return to prison on technical violations, according to criminal system experts. California is the only state that places all prisoners on parole at release, but now hundreds of low-level offenders will be released without close supervision from their parole officers. The effort represents a “seismic shift,” said Joan Petersilia, a criminologist at Stanford Law School and a longtime scholar of the state’s prisons. The prison system costs the state $8 billion annually, about 11 percent of the state budget. [The New York Times]
headline_main: Sampler: California Begins Its Prison Inmate Reduction Plan, and Walnut Creek Pot Club Closes

abstract: A look at news of interest in the San Francisco Bay Area.
snippet: A look at news of interest in the San Francisco Bay Area.
lead_paragraph: San Francisco Schools Face Further Cuts  | With the schools budget likely to face a $113 million gap between its programs and its financial resources, the superintendent, Carlos Garcia, plans to eliminate 100 teachers, put employees across the system on furlough and sharply trim summer school and teacher training programs. “There are things in here that go against my beliefs,” Mr. Garcia said, calling the planned cuts “horrible and deplorable.” The teachers’ union said its consent would be needed for some of the cuts. [The San Francisco Chronicle, The Associated Press]
headline_main: Sampler: More Cuts for City Schools and Another Amazing Gerhart

abstract: Was a slip on Notre Dame’s final play a bit of karmic retribution for Charlie Weis?
snippet: Was a slip on Notre Dame’s final play a bit of karmic retribution for Charlie Weis?
lead_paragraph: 1. Did Charlie Weis get his agricultural comeuppance? After growing the grass to British Open rough lengths five years ago to slow down U.S.C., the turf turned against Notre Dame today. On the game’s final play, with Notre Dame trailing by 7 and on the 4-yard line, Weis said that the intended Notre Dame receiver, Duval Kamara, slipped coming out of his turn. He said Kamara would have been open because U.S.C. had double-teamed Golden Tate. Kamara’s slip on the Irish turf continued Weis’s winless streak against U.S.C. and was perhaps some karmic retribution for Weis growing the grass so long in 2005.
